changes.value:
`swissarmyhammer-directory/src/directory.rs:527-530`

```rust
let dir = std::env::var("XDG_CONFIG_HOME")
    .ok()
    .map(|_| ())
    .unwrap_or(());
let _ = dir;
```

This code reads the env var, maps anything to `()`, and discards the result. It appears to be leftover scaffolding that was intended to save the previous value for restoration. The test does not restore the env var if it was set before the test ran, so it permanently clobbers `XDG_CONFIG_HOME` for the process, which can affect other concurrently running tests.

Suggestion: Remove this dead block and use `serial_test::serial` to prevent interference, or use a proper save/restore pattern:
```rust
let saved = std::env::var("XDG_CONFIG_HOME").ok();
// ... test ...
match saved {
    Some(v) => std::env::set_var("XDG_CONFIG_HOME", v),
    None => std::env::remove_var("XDG_CONFIG_HOME"),
}
```

